CASEOUS LYMPHADENITIS, CAPRINE - USA: (CALIFORNIA)
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Mon 26 Oct 2009
Source: Red Bluff Daily News [edited]
<http://www.redbluffdailynews.com/ci_13643906>


Vet claims goat was a health risk at Fair
-----------------------------------------
The Tehama District Fair Board heard 20 Oct 2009 from Sandy Flournoy,
a veterinarian at Antelope Veterinary Hospital, about an issue
regarding a possible exposure at the fair to an animal with caseous
lymphadenitis (CL).

"If an animal has scars and is a carrier it is a risk," Flournoy
said. "If the abscess broke and drained the animal should have been
excused. It is a human pathogen and is transmittable to all species."

Although Flournoy did not see the animal herself, she said the
disease is contagious enough that even the slight chance of it being
present should be dealt with seriously.

The animal in question was a market goat, which several parents,
including one 4-H mother present Tuesday [20 Oct 2009], said they saw
had an abscess that had broken and drained.

Flournoy said regardless of whether or not it was CL, the animal
should have been excused.

"All the animals were looked at by a licensed practicing veterinarian
and he made a judgment call," said Fair CEO Mark Eidman. "I have to
back his decision. He inspected the animal prior to the fair opening
[24 Sep 2009] and he did not note any health risk to the animal or
the public."

Fair Livestock manager Nancy May told the board in a letter that all
animals were checked by a licensed veterinarian on Wednesday [23 Sep
2009] before the fair and again before the animals went on the scales.

After being approached by parents of exhibitors regarding an animal
with an oozing abscess, May said she looked at the animal and did not
see anything, but also asked a licensed veterinarian to inspect.

"I felt at no time that I dropped the ball putting any livestock,
exhibitor or fairgoer at risk," May said. "I do not feel that the
Tehama District Fairground is unsafe for livestock or that any person
connected with the fair is uncaring of the welfare of its livestock
patrons. How much further do you go past a licensed veterinarian?"

A few members of the Manton 4-H came to the meeting including one
girl who addressed the board. The girl said she could not believe
more of an effort wasn't taken to protect the animals, public, and
especially the children who were exposed to the goat.

Fair Board director Farrell Shatswell assured the audience that the
fair board would do all that it could to keep the fair safe. "I
personally Cloroxed [cleaned with bleach] the metal pens and
everywhere the alleged animal was," Eidman said.

The fair board meets at 1 p.m. on the 3rd Tuesday of the month at the
fairground.

[Byline: Julie Zeeb]

