<promed@promedmail.org>

[Caseous abscessation of lymph nodes and internal organs caused by
_Corynebacterium pseudotuberculosis_ occurs worldwide and is widely
distributed throughout North America. While this disease carries a
name similar to tuberculosis, it is not tuberculosis. It is an
important endemic infection in regions with large sheep and goat
populations, especially market or meat goats. Economic losses result
mostly from condemnation and trim of infected carcasses and
devaluation of hides. Caseous lymphadenitis is also a cause of
ill-thrift and sudden death in animals with internal abscesses.
Although principally an infection of sheep and goats, sporadic
disease also occurs in horses and cattle, camelids, water buffalo,
wild ruminants, primates, pigs, and fowl. It rarely causes regional
lymphadenitis in humans.

Caseous lymphadenitis is a chronic, recurring disease. A slowly
enlarging, localized, and non painful abscess may develop either at
the point of entry into the skin or in the regional lymph node
(superficial or external form), from which it may spread via the
blood or lymphatic system and cause abscessation of internal lymph
nodes or organs (visceral or internal form). Initial infection may
cause no clinical signs or may be accompanied by high fever,
anorexia, anemia, and cellulitis at the infection site. Superficial
abscesses enlarge and may rupture and discharge infectious pus.

Other less common manifestations include caseous bronchopneumonia,
arthritis, abortion, CNS abscessation often occurring in the
pituitary gland, abscessation of a vertebral body causing paresis or
paralysis, scrotal abscessation, and rarely, mastitis. Scrotal
(inguinal) abscesses can cause temporary infertility in rams. The
incidence of abscesses steadily increases with age; clinical disease
is more prevalent in adults, and up to 40 percent of animals in a
flock can have superficial abscesses.

The diagnosis can usually be based on clinical signs and flock
history. For definitive diagnosis, an aspirate of an intact abscess
should be submitted for bacteriologic examination; _C
pseudotuberculosis_ can easily be isolated, although it may be
recovered in mixed culture with other pyogenic organisms. Suppurative
lymphadenitis and abscesses can also be caused by various other
pyogenic organisms, such as _Arcanobacterium (Actinomyces) pyogenes_,
_Staphylococcus aureus_, _Pasteurella multocida_, and occasionally
anaerobes such as _Fusobacterium necrophorum_.

Although the organism is susceptible to penicillin, treatment with
antibiotics is usually not attempted because the formation of
abscesses limits their penetration and effectiveness.

Commercial vaccines, currently only licensed for use in sheep, reduce
the incidence and prevalence of caseous lymphadenitis within a flock,
but they neither prevent all new infections nor cure animals already
infected. Currently, all contain phospholipase D toxoid, and some
also contain killed whole bacterial cells. Usually, _Clostridium
tetani_ and _C. perfringens_ type D, along with other clostridial
antigens, are included in the vaccine.

Although rare, caseous lymphadenitis in man can be a serious disease
requiring hospitalization, prolonged antibiotic therapy, and even
surgery. Clients should be made aware of this and advised to take
appropriate precautions when handling infected sheep. The organism
generally enters the body through a scrape or a cut.

While the disease in man is rare, it can occur. The risk to most
humans at the fair is likely low. The attending veterinarian may not
have noticed the abscess if it was small when the animal arrived at
the facilities. Nevertheless a ruptured abscess can put other animals
at risk of the disease.

Many fairs give the appearance of checking the animals for disease
and zoonotics, but sometimes the veterinarians working the fairs are
under strict orders to keep the most participants and overlook
anything except the most serious of diseases.

The fairs should showcase the best of the best, not the best that
have learned to get around the rules. Often time ringworm and warts
are covered over with iodine and shoe polish to get past the cursory
veterinary inspection and be accepted into the show.

The question should be asked, why not teach the participants,
regardless of age, to be upright and truthful and showcase the best
instead of finding ways to get around the rules and cheating to win?

Portions of this comment have been extracted from
<http://www.vetmanual.org/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/10801.htm> and
<http://www.sheepvetsoc.org.uk/NewsCL.htm>. - Mod.TG]

